message: >-
  If you use these patterns in your systems, research, or publications, please
  cite this repository using the metadata below.
type: software
title: >-
  payments-agent-audit: Governance Patterns for Autonomous AI Agents in
  Regulated Payments
authors:
  - family-names: Bhaduri
    given-names: Kunjar
    affiliation: North Texas Capital Investments
    website: "https://www.linkedin.com/in/kunjarbhaduri"

repository-code: "https://github.com/linus10x/payments-agent-audit"
url: "https://github.com/linus10x/payments-agent-audit"
abstract: >-
  Reference governance patterns and runnable implementations for audit-ready
  autonomous AI agents in regulated payments. Carries five Autonomy-Ladder
  governance primitives built to a corrected specification — autonomy-level
  classification (A0 through A4) with an irreversibility promotion gate,
  sovereign veto with a fail-closed production mode and authenticated-principal
  binding, a hash-chain audit ledger with a branched genesis seed (external
  witness anchoring is a deployer-wired interface, mandatory in production mode),
  a DEFCON-style risk-state machine with a transition-direction
  guard, and an effective-challenge harness that rejects self-challenge and
  records an independence attestation. Adds payments-specific controls: an
  implemented OFAC sanctions screening workflow (fuzzy match + hit disposition
  against a pluggable list, no list bundled), BSA/AML SAR timeliness and the
  Travel Rule, Regulation E error resolution, sponsor-bank / BaaS oversight, and
  a first-class rail-finality / irreversibility dimension that gates
  autonomy-level promotion for instant-rail (FedNow/RTP) programs while modeling
  ACH as non-final. Maps to U.S. payments authorities including OFAC (31 CFR Part
  501 / IEEPA), FinCEN BSA/AML (31 CFR 1020.320, 1010.410(f), 1022), the FedNow
  Service (Regulation J, 12 CFR Part 210 Subpart C), the RTP Operating Rules, the
  Nacha Operating Rules, Regulation E (12 CFR 1005.11), the June 2023 Interagency
  Guidance on Third-Party Relationships, and the BSA five-year retention floor (31
  CFR 1010.430). The claim layer matches implemented reality; documented patterns
  are labeled as such. Patterns extracted from a private quantitative options
  program operating in paper-trading Phase 0 — no live capital deployed.
keywords:
  - AI governance
  - autonomous agents
  - payments
  - OFAC
  - sanctions screening
  - BSA/AML
  - real-time payments
  - regulated AI
  - audit trail
  - human-in-the-loop
